// MARK: - Measure Descriptions

"measure.gripStrength.description" = "Grip strength is a strong indicator of overall physical reserve and recovery. Measure with a dynamometer and log your best effort.";
"measure.hrvSDNN.description" = "Heart rate variability measures the tiny differences in timing between each heartbeat — a sign of how well your body's rest-and-recover system is working. It's considered the gold standard for recovery tracking. A higher value means your nervous system is more resilient and ready to handle stress.";
"measure.restingHeartRate.description" = "Your resting heart rate is how many times your heart beats per minute when you're fully at rest. When it's lower than your usual baseline, your cardiovascular system is well recovered. An elevated reading often signals that stress, illness, or incomplete recovery is putting extra load on your body.";
"measure.sleepDuration.description" = "This is the total hours of sleep recorded from your phone or watch. Sleep is when your body does most of its repair work — muscles rebuild, hormones rebalance, and memories consolidate. Most adults need 7–9 hours, and more sleep generally means better recovery.";
"measure.tapFrequency.description" = "This measures how fast you can tap in a quick 10-second test, which reveals how efficiently your brain is sending signals to your muscles. Think of it as a readiness check for your motor system. If you're tapping slower than your baseline, your nervous system may be fatigued.";
"measure.tapStability.description" = "While tap frequency checks speed, stability checks rhythm — how evenly spaced your taps are. A steady, consistent rhythm means your nervous system has good fine motor control. When you're fatigued, your tapping becomes more erratic even if you don't feel tired.";
"measure.reactionTime.description" = "This measures how quickly you respond to something appearing on screen — a direct window into your alertness and cognitive sharpness. Slower reactions than your baseline usually point to sleep debt, mental fatigue, or incomplete recovery.";
"measure.sleepQuality.description" = "Your own rating of how well you slept, from restless to deeply refreshing. This captures things that hours alone can't — like whether you woke up multiple times, had vivid dreams, or simply feel unrested despite a full night.";
"measure.muscleSoreness.description" = "A quick self-check on how your muscles feel right now. Higher ratings mean less soreness. Persistent or unusual soreness is your body's way of saying your muscles have not fully repaired yet and could benefit from lighter activity or rest.";
"measure.energyLevel.description" = "A simple rating of how much energy you feel you have right now. This intuitive gut check often picks up on things the objective tests miss — like emotional stress, motivation, or coming down with something. Higher means you feel more ready to go.";

// MARK: - Measure Direction Hints

